var t={path:"cdj-wav-32bit-float-fix",title:"CDJ E-8304/E-8305: 32-bit Float WAV Fix \u2014 Pioneer CDJ",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8304 or E-8305 on a WAV from Ableton, Logic, or FL Studio? The file is 32-bit float \u2014 no CDJ supports it. Convert it to 24-bit integer here.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8304 / E-8305: How to Fix 32-bit Float WAV Files for Pioneer CDJ Playback",errorDisplay:"E-8304 / E-8305",hook:"You bounce a WAV from Ableton Live, Logic Pro, or FL Studio, drag it into rekordbox, and the CDJ immediately throws E-8304 or E-8305 \u2014 even though the file is perfectly valid 44.1 kHz stereo audio. The problem is invisible in any file manager and in most audio players: the WAV file uses 32-bit float sample encoding (format tag 0x0003), and no Pioneer CDJ \u2014 including the CDJ-3000 \u2014 can decode 32-bit float audio. The fix is a one-command re-encode to 24-bit integer PCM.",technicalCause:"The WAV specification defines several sample formats via the format tag field in the file header. WAVE_FORMAT_PCM (0x0001) covers 8-bit, 16-bit, and 24-bit integer audio. WAVE_FORMAT_IEEE_FLOAT (0x0003) covers 32-bit and 64-bit floating-point audio. Pioneer CDJs only support WAVE_FORMAT_PCM at 16-bit or 24-bit resolution. 32-bit float is the internal processing format of virtually every modern DAW \u2014 Ableton Live, Logic Pro X, FL Studio, Bitwig Studio, and Pro Tools all operate internally at 32-bit float. When you export or bounce a project without explicitly choosing a bit depth, many DAWs default to 32-bit float, which produces a WAV the CDJ cannot play. The file plays without issues on your computer because desktop audio engines natively support floating-point audio. CDJ hardware decoders do not. This issue affects all current Pioneer DJ players: CDJ-3000, CDJ-2000NXS2, CDJ-2000NXS, XDJ-XZ, and XDJ-1000MK2.",manualSolution:{intro:"Converting a 32-bit float WAV to 24-bit integer PCM is lossless in practice \u2014 the audible dynamic range of 24-bit integer (144 dB) exceeds what any club PA system can reproduce. The following tools perform the conversion.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI) \u2014 recommended",command:"ffmpeg -i input_32float.wav -acodec pcm_s24le -rf64 never output_24bit.wav",detail:"`-acodec pcm_s24le` sets 24-bit signed integer PCM little-endian (WAVE_FORMAT_PCM 0x0001). `-rf64 never` forces a standard RIFF header instead of an RF64 or EXTENSIBLE container. Without `-rf64 never`, ffmpeg may output WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE for 24-bit audio, which also causes CDJ errors. For 16-bit output (CDJ-900/CDJ-900NXS compatibility) replace `pcm_s24le` with `pcm_s16le`."},{tool:"SoX (CLI)",command:"sox input_32float.wav -e signed-integer -b 24 output_24bit.wav",detail:"SoX always writes WAVE_FORMAT_PCM headers and handles float-to-integer conversion correctly. Install via `brew install sox` on macOS or `apt install sox` on Linux. The `-e signed-integer -b 24` flags specify 24-bit integer output."},{tool:"Ableton Live \u2014 prevent on export",detail:'Go to File \u2192 Export Audio/Video. Under "Bit Depth", select "24-Bit" instead of "32-Bit" or "32-Bit Float". Ableton 11 and 12 default to 32-bit float for WAV exports. Setting 24-bit here produces a CDJ-compatible file directly without any post-export conversion.'},{tool:"Logic Pro \u2014 prevent on export",detail:'Go to File \u2192 Bounce \u2192 Project or Section. Under "Bit Depth", select "24" from the dropdown. Logic Pro defaults to 24-bit for standard bounces, but mastering sessions and custom export presets may override this. Always verify the bit depth before finalising your export.'},{tool:"FL Studio \u2014 prevent on export",detail:'Go to File \u2192 Export \u2192 Wave File. Under "Bit depth", select "24 bit". FL Studio defaults to 32-bit float for WAV renders. Change this in the export dialog each time, or create a saved preset with 24-bit selected.'}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready detects 32-bit float WAV files by reading the format tag and bits-per-sample fields from the WAV header during upload. Affected files are automatically re-encoded to 24-bit signed integer PCM using ffmpeg with the correct flags. The fix is applied in batch across your entire library without manual intervention.",faq:[{question:"What is the difference between 32-bit float and 32-bit integer WAV?",answer:"32-bit float (IEEE 754 floating-point) and 32-bit integer are both 4-byte-per-sample formats, but they encode sample values differently. 32-bit float is the internal processing format of DAWs and supports values outside the [-1, 1] range (headroom above 0 dBFS). 32-bit integer stores fixed-point values with no headroom. Pioneer CDJs support neither \u2014 only 16-bit and 24-bit signed integer (WAVE_FORMAT_PCM) are supported."},{question:"Does converting from 32-bit float to 24-bit integer lose audio quality?",answer:"24-bit integer provides approximately 144 dB of dynamic range, which exceeds the capability of any DJ equipment or club PA system by a large margin. Any audio content that was within 0 dBFS (no clipping) in the 32-bit float source is preserved entirely in the 24-bit output. If the 32-bit float file contains samples above 0 dBFS (legal in floating-point), clipping may occur \u2014 but this indicates a problem with the mix level, not the conversion."},{question:"Why does my 32-bit float file play in rekordbox but not on the CDJ?",answer:"rekordbox desktop uses a software audio engine (Core Audio on macOS, Windows Media Foundation on Windows) that natively supports 32-bit float audio decoding. CDJ hardware decoders follow the WAV specification strictly and only support WAVE_FORMAT_PCM (0x0001). This discrepancy is the defining symptom: the file works everywhere on your computer but consistently fails on the physical CDJ."},{question:"Does this issue affect AIFF files too?",answer:"AIFF also supports 32-bit float encoding (via the COMM chunk compression type field). Pioneer CDJs only support uncompressed PCM AIFF. An AIFF file exported at 32-bit float from a DAW will trigger the same CDJ error. The fix is the same: re-encode to 24-bit integer using ffmpeg or SoX. See all E-8304 and E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8304 and /cdj-error-e-8305."}]};var o={path:"cdj-wav-extensible-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE WAV Fix (Bandcamp)",description:"CDJ shows E-8305 on a WAV downloaded from Bandcamp or exported via ffmpeg? It's a WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE header. Here's how to fix it.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: How to Fix WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE WAV Files for Pioneer CDJ Playback",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:'You download a WAV from Bandcamp, drag it into rekordbox, and everything looks fine \u2014 until you load it on your Pioneer CDJ and get "DATA FORMAT ERROR E-8305". The file is a perfectly valid 16-bit or 24-bit WAV, the sample rate is 44.1 kHz, and your DAW plays it without complaint. The problem is invisible to most software: the WAV file uses a WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE header (format tag 0xFFFE) instead of the standard PCM header (0x0001) that Pioneer CDJs require.',technicalCause:"The WAV specification defines several format tags in the file header (bytes 20\u201321). Pioneer CDJs support only WAVE_FORMAT_PCM (0x0001) \u2014 standard uncompressed 16-bit or 24-bit stereo audio. WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE (0xFFFE) is a Microsoft extension introduced for multichannel audio and sample formats above 16-bit. Even when the audio data inside is standard stereo PCM, the presence of the 0xFFFE tag causes the CDJ decoder to reject the file and throw E-8305 (DATA FORMAT ERROR). Bandcamp encodes many of its WAV downloads with the EXTENSIBLE header \u2014 particularly for tracks mastered at 24-bit depth. ffmpeg versions 4.0 and above also default to WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE when encoding 24-bit WAV unless explicitly told otherwise. Tools like Ableton Live, Bitwig Studio, and some hardware recorders produce the same header under certain export conditions. This issue affects all Pioneer CDJ and XDJ players \u2014 no firmware version has introduced WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE support.",manualSolution:{intro:"The fix is to re-encode the file to WAVE_FORMAT_PCM (0x0001) without changing the audio content. The following tools force the correct format tag.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI) \u2014 recommended",command:"ffmpeg -i input_extensible.wav -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 -rf64 never output_pcm.wav",detail:"The key flag is `-rf64 never`, which forces ffmpeg to write a standard RIFF/PCM header instead of an EXTENSIBLE or RF64 container. `-acodec pcm_s24le` sets 24-bit signed PCM little-endian. `-ar 44100` sets 44.1 kHz. For 16-bit output replace `pcm_s24le` with `pcm_s16le`. Without `-rf64 never`, ffmpeg 4+ will output EXTENSIBLE again for 24-bit audio."},{tool:"SoX (CLI)",command:"sox input_extensible.wav -e signed-integer -b 24 output_pcm.wav",detail:"SoX always writes WAVE_FORMAT_PCM headers and is a reliable alternative to ffmpeg for bulk conversion. Install via `brew install sox` on macOS or `apt install sox` on Linux. The `-e signed-integer -b 24` flags ensure 24-bit integer output."},{tool:"Audacity",detail:'Open the file in Audacity. Go to File \u2192 Export \u2192 Export as WAV. In the format dialog, select "WAV (Microsoft)" and "Signed 24-bit PCM". Audacity always writes WAVE_FORMAT_PCM headers regardless of the source file \u2014 this is a safe re-export option if you prefer a GUI.'},{tool:"Ableton Live (prevent on export)",detail:'If you are the producer exporting from Ableton: go to File \u2192 Export Audio/Video and set "Bit Depth" to 24 Bit and "Dither Options" to "Triangular". In Ableton 11 and 12, 24-bit WAV exports default to WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE. There is currently no GUI toggle in Ableton to force PCM headers \u2014 use ffmpeg post-export to convert the output file.'}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready scans every WAV header in your library for the WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE flag at upload. Affected files are automatically re-encoded to WAVE_FORMAT_PCM using ffmpeg with the correct flags \u2014 including all Bandcamp downloads and DAW exports. The fix is applied in batch across your entire library without changing filenames, folder structure, or rekordbox metadata.",faq:[{question:"Why do Bandcamp WAV downloads cause E-8305 on Pioneer CDJs?",answer:"Bandcamp masters and delivers many WAV files using the WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE header (0xFFFE), especially for 24-bit releases. This header is technically valid and plays on most software, but Pioneer CDJ hardware only supports WAVE_FORMAT_PCM (0x0001). Re-encoding the file with ffmpeg or SoX resolves the issue without any loss of audio quality."},{question:"My WAV is 16-bit stereo at 44.1 kHz \u2014 why does the CDJ still reject it?",answer:"The audio data format (bit depth, sample rate, channels) is separate from the container format tag in the WAV header. Even a 16-bit stereo 44.1 kHz file will trigger E-8305 if its header contains the EXTENSIBLE tag (0xFFFE). The CDJ checks the format tag before attempting to decode the audio data."},{question:"Does WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE affect audio quality?",answer:"No. WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE is a container format extension \u2014 the audio data inside is identical PCM. Converting from EXTENSIBLE to standard PCM is a lossless header rewrite; no audio information is changed."},{question:"Which CDJ models are affected by this issue?",answer:"All Pioneer CDJ and XDJ players are affected \u2014 this is a product-wide limitation, not specific to any generation. No firmware update across any model has introduced WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE support. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305."}]};var a={path:"cdj-wav-96khz-sample-rate-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: 96 kHz WAV / AIFF Not Playing \u2014 Fix",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on a 96 kHz WAV or AIFF file? Hi-res audio is not supported. Learn how to resample to 44.1 kHz or 48 kHz for CDJ playback.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: How to Fix 96 kHz WAV and AIFF Files for Pioneer CDJ Playback",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:'You purchase a hi-res 96 kHz WAV or AIFF from Beatport, HDtracks, or Bandcamp, import it into rekordbox, and your CDJ immediately throws "DATA FORMAT ERROR E-8305". The file is high quality, lossless audio \u2014 but no Pioneer CDJ supports 96 kHz or 88.2 kHz sample rates, regardless of bit depth. The fix is a sample rate conversion to 44.1 kHz or 48 kHz before the gig.',technicalCause:'Pioneer CDJs officially support WAV and AIFF files at 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz only. This applies to all bit depths (16-bit and 24-bit) and all Pioneer CDJ and XDJ models. 96 kHz and 88.2 kHz are common "hi-res audio" sample rates used by streaming stores, label deliverables, and mastering engineers \u2014 but the audio hardware inside Pioneer CDJs cannot process sample rates above 48 kHz. The E-8305 error is thrown during format validation before playback begins. Note: rekordbox desktop software supports 96 kHz playback, which is why the file analyses and previews correctly in the application but fails on the physical unit.',manualSolution:{intro:"Sample rate conversion (resampling) to 44.1 kHz produces a CDJ-compatible file with no perceptible quality loss on a dance-floor system.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI)",command:"ffmpeg -i input_96khz.wav -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 output_44khz.wav",detail:"`-ar 44100` instructs ffmpeg to resample to 44.1 kHz. `-acodec pcm_s24le` outputs 24-bit signed PCM \u2014 CDJ-compatible and preserves the bit depth of the source. For 48 kHz output replace `44100` with `48000`. ffmpeg uses a high-quality resampler by default. For AIFF files, replace the output filename extension with `.aiff`."},{tool:"SoX (CLI)",command:"sox input_96khz.wav -r 44100 output_44khz.wav rate -v -s",detail:"The `rate -v -s` flags enable SoX's Very High Quality resampler, which applies a steep anti-aliasing filter before downsampling. This is the most accurate resampling option in SoX and is recommended for music production deliverables."},{tool:"rekordbox (built-in)",detail:'In rekordbox 6.x, right-click any track in your library and select "Export to Device" \u2014 you can set a target sample rate in Preferences \u2192 CDJ/XDJ. Alternatively, under Preferences \u2192 Audio, set "Sample Rate" to 44.1 kHz and re-analyse the track. Note: rekordbox conversion quality varies \u2014 ffmpeg or SoX give more control over the resampling algorithm.'},{tool:"Logic Pro X / Ableton Live",detail:'Open the file in your DAW and export/bounce at 44.1 kHz or 48 kHz, 24-bit WAV. In Logic: File \u2192 Bounce \u2192 Project, set "Sample Rate" to 44100. In Ableton: Preferences \u2192 Record/Warp/Launch, set "Sample Rate" to 44100, then export via File \u2192 Export Audio/Video.'}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready detects any WAV or AIFF file with a sample rate outside the CDJ-supported range (above 48 kHz or below 32 kHz) during library upload. Flagged files are automatically resampled to 44.1 kHz using a high-quality algorithm \u2014 your entire library is processed in a single batch without manual steps.",faq:[{question:"Does resampling from 96 kHz to 44.1 kHz reduce audio quality?",answer:"Not in any meaningful way on a club PA system. 96 kHz audio contains frequencies above 20 kHz which are inaudible to humans. A high-quality resampler applies an anti-aliasing filter and reduces the sample rate cleanly. The audible frequency content (20 Hz\u201320 kHz) is preserved entirely. 24-bit PCM at 44.1 kHz is the industry standard for DJ playback and mastering delivery."},{question:"Should I convert to 44.1 kHz or 48 kHz for CDJ playback?",answer:"44.1 kHz is the better choice for music that originated at 44.1 kHz (most commercial releases). Converting from 96 kHz to 44.1 kHz involves a clean integer-ratio relationship (96/44.1 requires resampling, but any good SRC handles this). 48 kHz is acceptable and equally supported by CDJs \u2014 use it if your source material was recorded at 48 kHz (video production, broadcast)."},{question:"Why does my 96 kHz file play in rekordbox but not on the CDJ?",answer:"rekordbox desktop uses a software audio engine that supports 96 kHz playback. The CDJ hardware uses an embedded decoder with a fixed set of supported sample rates (44.1 kHz and 48 kHz). This mismatch is a known source of confusion and is not fixed by any firmware update \u2014 you must convert the file."},{question:"Does the CDJ-3000 support 96 kHz?",answer:"No. Despite being Pioneer's flagship player, the CDJ-3000 does not support 96 kHz WAV or AIFF files. Pioneer officially documents 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz as the supported sample rates for all WAV and AIFF playback. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305."}]};var i={path:"cdj-mp3-vbr-seek-fix",title:"CDJ VBR MP3 Seek Problem: Missing Xing Header Fix",description:"Your CDJ waveform is wrong or the track length is inaccurate on VBR MP3 files? The Xing/Info header is missing. Learn how to fix VBR MP3 seek on Pioneer CDJs.",h1:"CDJ VBR MP3: Wrong Waveform or Track Length \u2014 How to Fix the Missing Xing Header",errorDisplay:"",hook:"Your CDJ shows a waveform that does not match the actual audio, the displayed track length is slightly wrong, or seeking jumps to the wrong position in a VBR MP3. There is no error code \u2014 the track loads and plays \u2014 but the waveform display and skip-to-position behaviour are inaccurate. The cause is a VBR (variable bitrate) MP3 file that is missing its Xing or Info header, the index that tells the CDJ how to navigate the file correctly.",technicalCause:"Variable bitrate MP3 encodes each frame at a different bitrate depending on the complexity of the audio content. This makes accurate seeking difficult: without a table of contents (TOC), the decoder cannot calculate where a given timestamp sits in the file. The Xing header (for true VBR) and the Info header (for CBR encoded by LAME) are metadata frames placed at the start of the MP3 that contain a TOC and the total number of frames. When the Xing/Info header is absent \u2014 which happens with older encoders, some download sources, and files stripped by ID3 tag editors \u2014 the CDJ falls back to an inaccurate linear estimation based on average bitrate. This produces waveforms that appear compressed or stretched and seek positions that are off by several seconds. In rare cases, a corrupted Xing header can also cause E-8306 if rekordbox wrote cue points based on incorrect timestamps that no longer match after the CDJ recalculates track length.",manualSolution:{intro:"The fix is to add or rebuild the Xing/Info header without re-encoding the audio data. This is a lossless operation \u2014 the MP3 audio frames are not touched.",steps:[{tool:"mp3val (adds missing header)",command:"mp3val -f input_novbr.mp3 -o output_fixed.mp3",detail:"mp3val scans the MP3 frame structure and adds a Xing TOC if one is missing. This is lossless \u2014 no audio re-encoding happens. Download at mp3val.sourceforge.net or via `brew install mp3val` on macOS."},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 rebuild header",command:"ffmpeg -i input_novbr.mp3 -acodec copy -id3v2_version 3 output_fixed.mp3",detail:"`-acodec copy` copies the audio stream without re-encoding. ffmpeg rewrites the container and adds a proper Xing/Info header in the process. This is the fastest method for bulk processing."},{tool:"LAME (re-encode with Xing)",command:"lame --decode input_novbr.mp3 - | lame -V 0 --add-id3v2 - output_vbr_xing.mp3",detail:"This two-stage approach decodes the MP3 to raw PCM and re-encodes with LAME at VBR quality 0 (highest). LAME always writes a Xing header. Use this only if the other methods do not resolve the seek issue \u2014 re-encoding reduces quality slightly."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready checks every MP3 for the presence and validity of the Xing or Info header. Files with missing or corrupt Xing headers are automatically repaired using a lossless header rebuild \u2014 no audio re-encoding, no quality loss. This prevents waveform display errors and inaccurate seek behaviour on all CDJ models.",faq:[{question:"What is a Xing header in an MP3 file?",answer:"A Xing header (also called Info header for CBR files) is a special metadata frame placed at the beginning of an MP3. It contains the total number of audio frames, a table of contents for accurate seeking, and quality flags written by the LAME encoder. CDJs and most hardware players use this header to render an accurate waveform display and enable accurate skip-to-position behaviour."},{question:"Does a missing Xing header cause an error code on the CDJ?",answer:"No \u2014 a missing Xing header does not produce an error code. The track loads and plays normally. The symptoms are a waveform display that looks wrong (compressed, stretched, or blank in sections) and seek positions that jump to incorrect timestamps. In rare cases a mismatched cue point (written by rekordbox) can cause E-8306 if the CDJ recalculates the track length differently from rekordbox."},{question:"Is fixing the Xing header a lossless operation?",answer:"Yes. Adding or rebuilding a Xing header using mp3val or ffmpeg with `-acodec copy` does not touch the audio frames. The audio data is identical before and after \u2014 only the index metadata at the start of the file is written."},{question:"What is the difference between a Xing header and an Info header?",answer:"Xing headers are written by LAME for true VBR files and contain a full TOC. Info headers are written by LAME for CBR files and contain frame count and quality information but no TOC (since CBR seeking is accurate by calculation). CDJs use both for accurate waveform rendering. Other encoders (Fraunhofer, Blade, early iTunes) may write neither."}]};var r={path:"cdj-mp3-corrupt-frame-fix",title:"CDJ E-8302: Corrupt MP3 Frame \u2014 Fix for CDJ-3000",description:"Pioneer CDJ-3000 shows E-8302 on an MP3 that plays fine on CDJ-2000NXS2? Corrupt or non-standard frames are the cause. Here's how to repair or re-encode.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8302: How to Fix Corrupt MP3 Frames on Pioneer CDJ-3000",errorDisplay:"E-8302",hook:'An MP3 plays without issues on your CDJ-2000NXS2, but the moment you load it on a CDJ-3000 it throws "CANNOT PLAY TRACK E-8302". This is one of the most confusing CDJ compatibility problems: the file is not broken, it just contains non-standard or slightly malformed MP3 frames that the stricter CDJ-3000 decoder refuses to tolerate. The CDJ-2000NXS2 is significantly more forgiving \u2014 files that pass there can still fail on the CDJ-3000.',technicalCause:"The MP3 format encodes audio in a sequence of frames, each containing a header and compressed audio data. The CDJ-3000 uses a new hardware decoder with stricter frame validation compared to the CDJ-2000NXS2. Common sources of corrupt or non-standard frames include: files ripped from damaged CDs, files that were re-encoded multiple times (lossy-to-lossy), files with truncated or padded frame data from broken download transfers, and files with non-standard free-format bitrate frames. Additionally, some older MP3 encoders (Xing, BladeEnc, early versions of LAME) produced frames that deviate from the ISO 11172-3 specification in ways that lenient decoders tolerate but strict ones reject. E-8302 on a WAV or AIFF file typically indicates a corrupted file that cannot be repaired \u2014 for MP3, a re-encode is almost always sufficient.",manualSolution:{intro:"The recommended approach is to re-encode the MP3 through a clean decode/encode cycle. If the audio source is available (e.g. a WAV master), always prefer re-encoding from the lossless source.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 re-encode (recommended)",command:"ffmpeg -i corrupt_input.mp3 -acodec libmp3lame -q:a 0 -id3v2_version 3 output_clean.mp3",detail:"`-acodec libmp3lame` uses the LAME encoder, which produces clean ISO-compliant frames. `-q:a 0` sets variable bitrate at maximum quality (equivalent to ~320 kbps). `-id3v2_version 3` writes ID3v2.3 tags, which are the most compatible across CDJ models. Note: re-encoding an already lossy MP3 reduces audio quality. If you have the WAV/AIFF source, use that as input instead."},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 re-encode from WAV source (best quality)",command:"ffmpeg -i source_master.wav -acodec libmp3lame -b:a 320k -id3v2_version 3 output_320.mp3",detail:"If you have the original WAV or AIFF master, always encode from that. `-b:a 320k` sets constant bitrate at 320 kbps. This produces a clean file with no quality loss from the re-encode stage."},{tool:"MP3val (repair without re-encode)",command:"mp3val -f input.mp3 -o output_repaired.mp3",detail:"MP3val is a free tool that scans for and repairs structural MP3 errors without decoding and re-encoding the audio. This preserves the original audio data and avoids quality loss. It handles truncated frames, garbage data between frames, and misaligned frame headers. Download at mp3val.sourceforge.net. Note: mp3val cannot fix frames where the audio data itself is corrupt."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready scans the frame structure of every MP3 in your library and flags files with non-standard or corrupt frames \u2014 including files that play on NXS2 but would fail on a CDJ-3000. For auto-fixable frame errors, the file is re-encoded using LAME at the original bitrate. Severe corruption where the audio data cannot be recovered is flagged for manual replacement.",faq:[{question:"Why does my MP3 play on CDJ-2000NXS2 but not on CDJ-3000?",answer:"The CDJ-3000 uses a new decoder chip with stricter MP3 frame validation. The CDJ-2000NXS2 decoder is more lenient and skips past minor frame errors. This means files with slightly malformed frames can pass on the NXS2 but fail with E-8302 on the CDJ-3000. The discrepancy is not a CDJ-3000 firmware bug \u2014 it is by design and the CDJ-3000 behaviour is ISO-compliant."},{question:"Does re-encoding an MP3 reduce audio quality?",answer:"Yes, re-encoding an MP3 to MP3 (lossy-to-lossy) reduces quality slightly due to generation loss. At 320 kbps this is generally not audible on a club PA system, but it is not ideal. If you have the original WAV or AIFF source, always use that for re-encoding. If the only source is the MP3, try MP3val first \u2014 it repairs frames without decoding."},{question:"Can E-8302 appear on WAV or AIFF files too?",answer:"Yes. E-8302 on a WAV or AIFF file typically means the file is severely corrupted and the audio data cannot be recovered. Unlike MP3, WAV/AIFF files with E-8302 usually require sourcing a fresh copy of the file \u2014 re-encoding is not helpful if the audio data is unreadable."},{question:"How do I know if my MP3 has corrupt frames before loading it on a CDJ?",answer:'Run `ffmpeg -v error -i yourfile.mp3 -f null -` in your terminal. ffmpeg will print any frame errors it encounters. If you see lines containing "invalid frame" or "missing header", the file has frame issues. Boothready performs this check automatically across your entire library.'}]};var s={path:"cdj-wav-multichannel-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: Multichannel WAV Fix (Bandcamp Surround)",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on a WAV with more than 2 channels? Multichannel and surround WAV files are not supported. Learn how to downmix to stereo.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: How to Fix Multichannel WAV Files for Pioneer CDJ Playback",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:'You download a WAV from Bandcamp or receive a stem delivery and the CDJ immediately shows "DATA FORMAT ERROR E-8305". The file plays perfectly in your DAW or media player, but no Pioneer CDJ can handle it. The reason is that the WAV contains more than two audio channels \u2014 a multichannel or surround format that CDJs do not support. This is increasingly common with Bandcamp releases that offer "enhanced stereo" or spatial audio downloads alongside the standard stereo WAV.',technicalCause:"Pioneer CDJs support WAV and AIFF files with exactly two channels (stereo) only. Multichannel WAV files \u2014 2.1, 5.1, 7.1, or any other configuration with more than 2 channels \u2014 trigger E-8305 regardless of sample rate or bit depth. Bandcamp introduced multichannel audio delivery in 2023, allowing artists to upload spatial or Atmos mixes alongside their stereo masters. When a buyer downloads the WAV, they may inadvertently receive the multichannel version. Multichannel WAV files almost always use the WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE header (0xFFFE) because the standard WAVE_FORMAT_PCM (0x0001) does not support more than 2 channels \u2014 meaning these files trigger E-8305 both due to the channel count and the EXTENSIBLE header. Stem packs, live recordings from multi-mic setups, and Dolby Atmos masters are other common sources.",manualSolution:{intro:"The fix is to downmix the file to stereo. A standard stereo downmix from a multichannel source preserves all audio energy using a standard channel matrix.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI) \u2014 recommended",command:"ffmpeg -i input_multichannel.wav -acodec pcm_s24le -ac 2 -ar 44100 output_stereo.wav",detail:'`-ac 2` sets the output to 2 channels (stereo). ffmpeg applies a standard Dolby Pro Logic downmix matrix automatically: front left/right pass through at 100%, center is mixed into both channels at -3 dB, and surround channels are mixed in at -3 dB. `-acodec pcm_s24le` outputs 24-bit PCM \u2014 ensuring CDJ compatibility. For 5.1 to stereo with a custom mix level, add `-filter_complex "pan=stereo|c0=FL+0.707*FC+0.707*BL|c1=FR+0.707*FC+0.707*BR"`.'},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 check channel count first",command:"ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=channels -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 input.wav",detail:"Run this command to confirm the channel count before converting. Output will be `channels=6` for 5.1, `channels=8` for 7.1, etc. If the output is `channels=2` the file is already stereo and the issue may be the EXTENSIBLE header instead \u2014 see /cdj-wav-extensible-fix."},{tool:"Audacity",detail:'Open the file in Audacity. If it shows more than 2 tracks in the project view, go to Tracks \u2192 Mix \u2192 Mix and Render to New Track. This creates a stereo mixdown. Delete the original multichannel tracks, then export via File \u2192 Export \u2192 Export as WAV, selecting "WAV (Microsoft)" and "Signed 24-bit PCM".'}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready detects multichannel WAV files by inspecting the channel count and EXTENSIBLE header flags during upload. Files with more than 2 channels are automatically downmixed to stereo using ffmpeg's standard channel matrix and re-encoded to WAVE_FORMAT_PCM. The fix handles both the channel count issue and the EXTENSIBLE header in a single pass.",faq:[{question:"How do I know if my Bandcamp WAV download is multichannel?",answer:"Run `ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=channels -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 yourfile.wav` in your terminal. A stereo file returns `channels=2`. Anything higher is multichannel. Alternatively, open the file in Audacity \u2014 a multichannel file will display more than 2 waveform tracks."},{question:"Will downmixing to stereo damage the audio?",answer:"For a standard stereo music release that was accidentally delivered in a multichannel container, downmixing to stereo recovers the original stereo content without loss. For a true spatial or surround mix, downmixing applies a channel matrix that collapses the spatial information \u2014 the result is a valid stereo file but without the spatial dimension. For club DJ use, stereo is always the correct target format."},{question:"Why does the multichannel WAV play fine on my computer but not on the CDJ?",answer:"Desktop operating systems and DAWs use software audio engines that handle multichannel WAV natively. Pioneer CDJ hardware decoders are built for stereo playback only. The CDJ rejects the file at the format validation stage before any audio decoding occurs."},{question:"Can E-8305 be caused by both the EXTENSIBLE header and multichannel at the same time?",answer:"Yes \u2014 and it usually is. Multichannel WAV files almost always use the WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE header because the standard PCM header does not support more than 2 channels. A downmix to stereo via ffmpeg with `-acodec pcm_s24le` resolves both issues in a single step. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305."}]};var n={path:"cdj-flac-unsupported-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: FLAC Not Supported on CDJ-2000NXS2 and Older",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on a FLAC file? FLAC is only supported on CDJ-3000 and CDJ-TOUR1 with the right firmware. Convert to WAV for all other models.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: FLAC Playback \u2014 Which CDJ Models Support It and How to Convert",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:`You put a FLAC file on your USB, load it on the CDJ, and get E-8305 "DATA FORMAT ERROR". FLAC is a lossless format \u2014 the audio quality is identical to WAV \u2014 but Pioneer's CDJ support for FLAC is model-dependent and firmware-dependent. On CDJ-2000NXS2 and all older models, FLAC is simply not supported and will always trigger E-8305. Even on the CDJ-3000, FLAC support requires a specific firmware version.`,technicalCause:"FLAC (Free Lossless Audio Codec) is a compressed lossless format. Unlike WAV and AIFF, FLAC requires a dedicated software decoder. Pioneer added FLAC support selectively across their product range: CDJ-3000 and CDJ-TOUR1 support FLAC from firmware 1.20 onwards (up to 96 kHz, 24-bit). CDJ-2000NXS2, CDJ-2000NXS, CDJ-2000, XDJ-XZ, XDJ-1000MK2, and all older models do not support FLAC in any firmware version. The E-8305 error is thrown because the CDJ cannot identify the format as playable. Note that rekordbox desktop supports FLAC analysis and preview for all models \u2014 this is a common source of confusion, as a FLAC file can be imported into a rekordbox library that targets a non-FLAC CDJ. Additionally, even on the CDJ-3000, FLAC files at 96 kHz will trigger E-8305 because 96 kHz is not a supported sample rate on any CDJ.",manualSolution:{intro:"Convert FLAC to WAV or AIFF for universal CDJ compatibility. This is a lossless decode \u2014 FLAC is lossless by definition, so the WAV output is bit-for-bit identical to the original uncompressed audio.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI) \u2014 batch convert all FLAC files",command:'for f in *.flac; do ffmpeg -i "$f" -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 "${f%.flac}.wav"; done',detail:'This shell loop converts all FLAC files in the current directory to 24-bit PCM WAV at 44.1 kHz. The output filename keeps the original name and replaces the `.flac` extension with `.wav`. On Windows, use: `for %f in (*.flac) do ffmpeg -i "%f" -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 "%~nf.wav"`'},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 single file",command:"ffmpeg -i input.flac -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 output.wav",detail:"`-acodec pcm_s24le` outputs 24-bit signed PCM little-endian WAV \u2014 the most compatible CDJ format. If the source FLAC is 16-bit, use `pcm_s16le` to avoid unnecessary upsampling. Check the source bit depth with `ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=bits_per_raw_sample input.flac`."},{tool:"fre:ac (GUI, Windows/macOS/Linux)",detail:'fre:ac is a free GUI audio converter that handles FLAC to WAV batch conversion. Add your FLAC files, set the output format to "Microsoft Wave Audio" with 16 or 24-bit PCM, and click Convert. Download at freac.org.'},{tool:"rekordbox (built-in export)",detail:'In rekordbox 6.x, you can set the export format for USB devices under Preferences \u2192 CDJ/XDJ. Set "Convert to WAV when exporting" and choose 24-bit, 44.1 kHz. When you export tracks to USB, rekordbox will automatically convert FLAC files. Note: this only applies to the USB export, not to the source files in your library.'}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready detects FLAC files and checks them against the target CDJ model set in your job configuration. If any target model does not support FLAC (CDJ-2000NXS2 or older), the file is automatically converted to 24-bit PCM WAV. If all targets are CDJ-3000 or CDJ-TOUR1 with compatible firmware, the FLAC file is passed through without conversion.",faq:[{question:"Does the CDJ-3000 support FLAC?",answer:"Yes, but only from firmware version 1.20 onwards, and only for FLAC files at 44.1 kHz or 48 kHz, 16-bit or 24-bit. FLAC files at 96 kHz will still trigger E-8305 even on the CDJ-3000. Check your firmware version under Utility \u2192 Firmware Version on the CDJ-3000."},{question:"Is converting FLAC to WAV a lossy operation?",answer:"No. FLAC is a lossless codec. Decoding a FLAC file to WAV produces a bit-for-bit identical copy of the original uncompressed audio. There is zero audio quality difference between a FLAC file and the WAV produced from it."},{question:"My FLAC plays fine in rekordbox \u2014 why does the CDJ reject it?",answer:"rekordbox desktop software supports FLAC playback and analysis for all CDJ target models, regardless of whether the physical hardware supports FLAC. This means a FLAC file can appear in your rekordbox library with cue points, waveforms, and BPM data \u2014 but still fail with E-8305 on a CDJ-2000NXS2. The CDJ hardware decoder is separate from the rekordbox software decoder."},{question:"Should I store my library as FLAC or WAV going forward?",answer:"For DJ use, WAV or AIFF 24-bit at 44.1 kHz is the most practical choice \u2014 universally compatible with all CDJ models, no conversion needed at the gig. FLAC is better for archival storage (smaller file size, lossless) but adds a conversion step for CDJ compatibility. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305."}]};var l={path:"cdj-aiff-compressed-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: Compressed AIFF-C File Fix (ALAW, ADPCM)",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on an AIFF file? It may be a compressed AIFF-C file (ALAW, \xB5Law, IMA ADPCM). CDJs only support uncompressed PCM AIFF. Here's the fix.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: How to Fix Compressed AIFF-C Files for Pioneer CDJ Playback",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:"Your CDJ shows E-8305 on an AIFF file that plays fine in iTunes, Logic, or any desktop player. The file extension is `.aiff` or `.aif`, so it looks like a standard audio file \u2014 but the CDJ refuses to play it. The likely cause is that the file is actually an AIFF-C (compressed AIFF) file, a variant of the AIFF format that uses a compressed codec such as ALAW, \xB5Law, or IMA ADPCM. Pioneer CDJs only support uncompressed PCM AIFF and will throw E-8305 on any compressed AIFF-C codec.",technicalCause:"The AIFF format has two variants: AIFF (uncompressed PCM) and AIFF-C (compressed, defined by the AIFC extension). Both use the `.aiff` or `.aif` extension, making them visually indistinguishable in Finder or Explorer. AIFF-C files contain a compression type identifier in the COMM chunk: ALAW (G.711 A-law), ulaw (G.711 \xB5-law), and ima4 (IMA ADPCM) are the most common. Apple's Core Audio framework, iTunes, Logic Pro, and QuickTime transparently decode AIFF-C \u2014 which is why the file plays on your Mac. Pioneer CDJs do not include decoders for these codecs. The CDJ checks the COMM chunk compression type before attempting playback and rejects anything other than NONE (uncompressed PCM). AIFF-C files are commonly produced by older Mac recording software, some hardware samplers, and audio hardware with built-in ALAW encoding (voice recorders, telephony equipment). The SOWT variant (little-endian PCM, used by some Apple tools) is also technically AIFF-C but is supported by CDJ-2000NXS2 and CDJ-3000 in most firmware versions.",manualSolution:{intro:"Convert the AIFF-C file to standard uncompressed AIFF PCM. This is a lossless decode \u2014 ALAW and \xB5Law are 8-bit codecs, so the decoded output will be 16-bit PCM representing the original dynamic range.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI) \u2014 recommended",command:"ffmpeg -i input_compressed.aiff -acodec pcm_s16be -ar 44100 output_pcm.aiff",detail:"`-acodec pcm_s16be` sets 16-bit signed PCM big-endian \u2014 the standard uncompressed AIFF codec. AIFF is big-endian by specification; using `pcm_s16be` ensures a proper AIFF container. `-ar 44100` sets the sample rate. For 24-bit output use `pcm_s24be`. To output WAV instead, change the extension to `.wav` and use `pcm_s24le`."},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 identify codec first",command:"ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=codec_name,codec_long_name -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 input.aiff",detail:"Run this to confirm the AIFF codec before converting. Output will show `codec_name=alaw`, `codec_name=adpcm_ima_qt`, or similar for compressed files. If it shows `codec_name=pcm_s16be` or `codec_name=pcm_s24be`, the file is already uncompressed PCM \u2014 the E-8305 may be caused by a different issue."},{tool:"Audacity",detail:'Open the AIFF-C file in Audacity (it decodes all AIFF-C variants automatically). Go to File \u2192 Export \u2192 Export as AIFF. In the format options, select "AIFF (Apple/SGI)" and "Signed 16-bit PCM" or "Signed 24-bit PCM". Audacity always exports uncompressed AIFF, which is CDJ-compatible.'},{tool:"Logic Pro X",detail:`Import the AIFF-C file into a Logic project. Bounce the track via File \u2192 Bounce \u2192 Project or Section. Set "File Format" to AIFF and "Resolution" to 16 Bit or 24 Bit. Logic Pro's bounce output is always uncompressed PCM AIFF.`}]},boothreadySolution:"boothready detects compressed AIFF-C files by reading the compression type from the COMM chunk of every AIFF file in your library. ALAW, \xB5Law, and IMA ADPCM files are automatically decoded and re-encoded as uncompressed 16-bit PCM AIFF \u2014 CDJ-compatible and with the original audio content preserved.",faq:[{question:"How do I tell if my AIFF file is compressed or uncompressed?",answer:"You cannot tell from the file extension \u2014 both AIFF and AIFF-C use `.aiff` or `.aif`. Run `ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=codec_name -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 yourfile.aiff` in your terminal. If the output is `codec_name=pcm_s16be` or `pcm_s24be`, the file is uncompressed. Any other codec name (alaw, ulaw, adpcm_ima_qt) means it is compressed AIFF-C."},{question:"Does ALAW or \xB5Law AIFF reduce audio quality?",answer:"Yes. ALAW and \xB5Law are 8-bit logarithmic codecs designed for voice telephony, not music. They have a dynamic range of approximately 56 dB, compared to 96 dB for 16-bit PCM. Decoding a \xB5Law AIFF-C to 16-bit PCM recovers the original 8-bit quality, but you cannot recover dynamic range that was lost during the original encoding. If you have the uncompressed source, always use that instead."},{question:"Which CDJ models are affected by compressed AIFF-C?",answer:"All current Pioneer DJ players: CDJ-3000, CDJ-2000NXS2, CDJ-2000NXS, XDJ-XZ, and XDJ-1000MK2. None include decoders for ALAW, \xB5Law, or IMA ADPCM AIFF-C. The SOWT variant (little-endian PCM AIFF-C) is supported on CDJ-2000NXS2 and CDJ-3000 but not on older models. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305."},{question:"Can I convert AIFF-C to WAV instead of AIFF for CDJ playback?",answer:"Yes. WAV and AIFF are equally supported on all Pioneer CDJs. Use `ffmpeg -i input.aiff -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 output.wav` to convert to 24-bit WAV. There is no audio quality difference between WAV and AIFF at the same bit depth and sample rate."}]};var d={path:"cdj-wav-corrupt-header",title:"CDJ E-8304: Corrupt WAV Header \u2014 Diagnosis and Fix",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8304 on a WAV file that plays on your computer? The WAV header may be corrupt or unreadable. Learn how to diagnose and repair it.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8304: Corrupt WAV Header \u2014 How to Diagnose and Fix",errorDisplay:"E-8304",hook:'Your CDJ shows "DECODE ERROR E-8304" on a WAV file that opens and plays fine in every software player on your computer. This is a strong indicator that the WAV file header \u2014 the first few hundred bytes that describe the file format, sample rate, bit depth, and data layout \u2014 is malformed or contains data the CDJ decoder cannot parse. Unlike format incompatibilities that can be fixed by re-encoding, a corrupt header may or may not be repairable depending on whether the audio data itself is intact.',technicalCause:"WAV files begin with a RIFF chunk containing format metadata: sample rate, bit depth, channel count, codec tag, and the position of the audio data. The CDJ hardware decoder reads this header strictly before attempting to decode audio. Common causes of corrupt or unreadable headers include: incomplete downloads or USB transfer interruptions that truncated the file, ID3 tag editors that wrote malformed or oversized metadata into the RIFF header, file repair tools that incorrectly reconstructed the RIFF chunk offsets, and files recovered from damaged storage media with partial header data. Desktop software players (Windows Media Player, VLC, foobar2000, macOS QuickTime) use lenient parsers that attempt to recover from header errors and often succeed \u2014 which is why the file plays on your computer but fails on the CDJ. E-8304 specifically indicates a decode-stage failure, meaning the header was read but the decoder could not initialise. If the header is completely unreadable, the CDJ may show E-8302 instead.",manualSolution:{intro:"The approach depends on whether the audio data is intact. Start with a header inspection and repair attempt before resorting to a full re-encode.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 diagnose first",command:"ffmpeg -v error -i suspect.wav -f null - 2>&1 | head -30",detail:'This command runs ffmpeg in analysis mode without producing output. Any header errors or decode warnings are printed to the terminal. Look for lines containing "invalid data", "missing chunk", or "truncated". If ffmpeg reports no errors, the WAV header is likely valid \u2014 the E-8304 may be caused by a format incompatibility (32-bit float, EXTENSIBLE tag) rather than corruption.'},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 repair by re-encode",command:"ffmpeg -i suspect.wav -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 -rf64 never repaired.wav",detail:"If ffmpeg can read the file despite header issues, re-encoding produces a clean file with a freshly written RIFF header. `-rf64 never` forces a standard RIFF container (not RF64 or extensible). This resolves header offset errors, malformed chunk sizes, and most ID3-related header corruption."},{tool:"wav-repair / Audio Repair Bench (GUI)",detail:'For files that ffmpeg cannot read at all, a dedicated WAV repair tool attempts to locate the raw PCM data in the file and reconstruct a valid header around it. "Audio Repair Bench" (Windows) and "Izotope RX" (macOS/Windows) can recover audio from files with completely missing or overwritten headers. These tools scan for the PCM data signature and rebuild the RIFF structure from scratch.'},{tool:"Get a fresh copy",detail:"If the file was downloaded, re-download it. If it was copied from a USB or external drive, re-copy from the original source. Header corruption from a bad download or interrupted USB transfer cannot always be repaired \u2014 a clean copy is faster and more reliable. After re-downloading, always verify with `ffmpeg -v error -i newfile.wav -f null -` before bringing to a gig."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready distinguishes between two types of corrupt WAV headers. Files with a valid RIFF/WAVE structure but a malformed format chunk \u2014 caused by ID3 editors, interrupted writes, or broken conversion tools \u2014 are repaired automatically via ffmpeg re-encode. Files with completely invalid RIFF magic bytes, where even ffmpeg cannot read the audio data, are flagged as unrecoverable with a clear error message. Either way, you know before the gig, not at the club.",faq:[{question:"Why does a corrupt WAV play on my computer but not on the CDJ?",answer:"Desktop software audio players use lenient, error-correcting parsers that attempt to recover from header problems and often succeed. CDJ hardware decoders are strict by design \u2014 they follow the WAV specification closely and reject files that do not conform. This means a corrupt WAV can play fine in VLC or Windows Media Player while consistently triggering E-8304 on every Pioneer CDJ it is loaded on."},{question:"Can I tell whether my WAV header is corrupt without a CDJ?",answer:"Yes. Run `ffmpeg -v error -i yourfile.wav -f null -` in your terminal. If the output contains header warnings or errors, the file has structural issues. A clean WAV produces no error output from this command."},{question:"What is the difference between E-8304 and E-8305 for corrupt files?",answer:"E-8304 (DECODE ERROR) indicates the CDJ read the header but the decoder failed to initialise \u2014 typically a format mismatch (32-bit float, unsupported codec) or header corruption at the format descriptor level. E-8305 (DATA FORMAT ERROR) indicates the format tag or container type is not recognised at all. Both codes can appear for corrupt headers depending on exactly where the corruption is located."},{question:"Is there a risk of the file becoming corrupt on a USB drive?",answer:"Yes. Unplugging a USB drive without safely ejecting it can corrupt files that were being written at the time. Always eject USB drives properly via the operating system before removing them. After copying tracks, run a verification pass with ffmpeg before the gig to catch any transfer errors."}]};var c={path:"cdj-alac-unsupported-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: Apple Lossless ALAC (.m4a) Not Supported",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on an Apple Lossless (.m4a) file? ALAC is not supported on any Pioneer CDJ. Convert to WAV or AIFF for CDJ playback.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: How to Fix Apple Lossless ALAC Files for Pioneer CDJ Playback",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:'You export your iTunes or Apple Music library to USB and the CDJ refuses to load your .m4a files with E-8305 "DATA FORMAT ERROR". Apple Lossless Audio Codec (ALAC) files use the same .m4a container as AAC \u2014 but no Pioneer CDJ supports ALAC, regardless of firmware version. Despite being lossless, ALAC requires a dedicated decoder that Pioneer has never included in their hardware.',technicalCause:'ALAC (Apple Lossless Audio Codec) is a lossless compression codec developed by Apple, stored in the MPEG-4 container (.m4a). It shares the .m4a file extension with AAC, which makes the two formats visually indistinguishable in Finder, Explorer, or rekordbox. Pioneer CDJs support AAC (.m4a, non-DRM) but do not include an ALAC decoder. The CDJ identifies the codec from the codec descriptor inside the MPEG-4 container: AAC uses mp4a/esds, ALAC uses alac/ALACSpecificBox. When it encounters an ALAC descriptor, it throws E-8305. ALAC files are commonly found in iTunes libraries where "Import Using: Apple Lossless Encoder" was selected, in Apple Music downloads (where lossless streaming is set as the download format), and in music purchased from the iTunes Store before 2009 (some older purchases were ALAC).',manualSolution:{intro:"Convert ALAC to WAV, AIFF, or AAC. Converting to WAV or AIFF is lossless \u2014 ALAC is lossless by definition, so the output is bit-for-bit identical to the original uncompressed audio.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI) \u2014 to WAV (lossless)",command:"ffmpeg -i input.m4a -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 output.wav",detail:'ffmpeg detects the ALAC codec automatically from the .m4a container. `-acodec pcm_s24le` outputs 24-bit signed PCM WAV \u2014 CDJ-compatible and lossless from the ALAC source. For a batch convert of all .m4a files in a folder: `for f in *.m4a; do ffmpeg -i "$f" -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 "${f%.m4a}.wav"; done`'},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 identify codec first",command:"ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=codec_name -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 input.m4a",detail:"Run this to confirm whether the .m4a file is ALAC or AAC before converting. ALAC returns `codec_name=alac`. AAC returns `codec_name=aac`. If the file is AAC and still triggers E-8305, the issue is likely DRM protection \u2014 see /cdj-aac-drm-protected."},{tool:"iTunes / Apple Music (macOS)",detail:"In the Music app (macOS), select the ALAC tracks, then go to File \u2192 Convert \u2192 Create WAV Version or Create AIFF Version. Apple Music converts ALAC losslessly to WAV or AIFF using the built-in Core Audio engine. The converted file appears in your library alongside the original."},{tool:"fre:ac (GUI, Windows/macOS/Linux)",detail:'fre:ac supports ALAC input and WAV/AIFF output. Add your .m4a files, set output to "Microsoft Wave Audio" at 24-bit PCM, and convert. Download at freac.org.'}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready identifies ALAC files by reading the codec descriptor from the MPEG-4 container \u2014 not by file extension. ALAC files are automatically converted to 24-bit PCM WAV in batch. AAC files in the same .m4a container are handled separately and passed through without conversion unless DRM is detected.",faq:[{question:"Does any Pioneer CDJ support Apple Lossless ALAC?",answer:"No. As of the current firmware, no Pioneer DJ player supports ALAC \u2014 including the CDJ-3000. Pioneer supports AAC (.m4a without DRM) but not the ALAC variant of the .m4a container. There is no indication from Pioneer that ALAC support will be added in future firmware."},{question:"My .m4a file plays in rekordbox \u2014 why does the CDJ reject it?",answer:"rekordbox desktop uses Apple Core Audio (macOS) or Windows Media Foundation for decoding, both of which support ALAC natively. The CDJ hardware decoder does not include an ALAC decoder. A file can therefore analyse and preview correctly in rekordbox while consistently failing with E-8305 on the physical CDJ."},{question:"Is converting ALAC to WAV a lossy operation?",answer:"No. ALAC is a lossless codec \u2014 decoding to WAV or AIFF produces a bit-for-bit identical copy of the original uncompressed audio. There is zero audio quality difference."},{question:"How do I stop iTunes from importing music as ALAC in future?",answer:'In the Music app on macOS, go to Music \u2192 Settings \u2192 Files \u2192 Import Settings and change "Import Using" from "Apple Lossless Encoder" to "WAV Encoder" or "AIFF Encoder". For DJ use, WAV at 44.1 kHz 24-bit is the most practical import format for direct CDJ compatibility. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305.'}]};var h={path:"cdj-aac-drm-protected",title:"CDJ E-8305: DRM-Protected AAC (iTunes Store) Cannot Play",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on an AAC file purchased from the iTunes Store? DRM-protected .m4p files cannot be played on any CDJ. Here's what you can do.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: DRM-Protected AAC Files Cannot Play on Pioneer CDJs",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:'You try to play a track you legitimately purchased from the iTunes Store on your CDJ and it immediately shows E-8305 "DATA FORMAT ERROR". The track plays fine in Apple Music on your Mac or iPhone, but no Pioneer CDJ can play it. The reason is FairPlay DRM (Digital Rights Management) \u2014 an encryption layer Apple applied to iTunes Store purchases before 2009. DRM-protected files are locked to your Apple ID and cannot be decoded by any third-party hardware.',technicalCause:`Apple's iTunes Store sold DRM-protected AAC files in the .m4p format from 2003 until 2009, when Apple switched to DRM-free iTunes Plus files (.m4a). FairPlay DRM encrypts the audio stream inside the MPEG-4 container. Only Apple-authorised software and hardware (iTunes, Apple Music, authorized Macs and iOS devices) can decrypt and play .m4p files. Pioneer CDJs do not implement the FairPlay DRM protocol and cannot decrypt these files \u2014 the audio data is unreadable to the CDJ decoder, resulting in E-8305. DRM-protected files use the .m4p extension (note the "p" for protected), while DRM-free AAC files use .m4a. Files purchased after 2009 or upgraded to iTunes Plus are .m4a and DRM-free. Older purchases may still be .m4p unless they were manually upgraded in the iTunes Store. Note: This is distinct from the ALAC issue \u2014 both .m4a and .m4p files can trigger E-8305, but for different reasons.`,manualSolution:{intro:"There is no direct technical fix for DRM \u2014 the encryption cannot be removed without authorisation. The following are the legitimate options available.",steps:[{tool:"Upgrade to iTunes Plus (Apple)",detail:"If your iTunes Store purchase is still available in the store, Apple may offer a free upgrade to the DRM-free iTunes Plus version. In the Music app on macOS, go to Account \u2192 Purchases and check whether an upgrade is available. iTunes Plus files are 256 kbps AAC (.m4a) without DRM and are fully compatible with Pioneer CDJs."},{tool:"Re-purchase as DRM-free",detail:"If the upgrade is not available, consider re-purchasing the track from a DRM-free store such as Beatport, Bandcamp, Traxsource, or the iTunes Store (all new purchases since 2009 are DRM-free). Bandcamp and Beatport offer WAV or AIFF downloads for most releases \u2014 the best format for CDJ playback."},{tool:"Record to audio (last resort)",detail:"On macOS, you can use a virtual audio cable tool (e.g. BlackHole or Soundflower) to route the output of Apple Music to a recording application while the track plays. This produces a real-time audio recording of the DRM-free output. This method produces a complete audio recording at the quality level Apple Music streams (256 kbps AAC or lossless). Whether this is permissible depends on your jurisdiction and the terms of your Apple Music licence."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready detects DRM-protected AAC files by checking for the FairPlay encryption marker in the MPEG-4 container. These files are flagged as unrepairable with a clear message \u2014 no auto-fix is attempted because the DRM cannot be bypassed. The report shows exactly which files are affected so you can source DRM-free replacements before the gig.",faq:[{question:"How do I know if my .m4a or .m4p file is DRM-protected?",answer:'Check the file extension: .m4p indicates DRM-protected, .m4a indicates DRM-free (though .m4a may be ALAC \u2014 see /cdj-alac-unsupported-fix). In the Music app on macOS, right-click the track \u2192 Get Info \u2192 File tab. If "Kind" shows "Protected AAC audio file", it is DRM-protected. Alternatively run `ffprobe -v error -i yourfile.m4p` \u2014 ffprobe will report a decryption error for protected files.'},{question:"Can I strip DRM from my iTunes purchases?",answer:"Technically it is possible with certain tools, but it is illegal in most jurisdictions under anti-circumvention laws (DMCA in the US, similar laws in the EU). Boothready does not offer or assist with DRM removal. The legitimate path is the iTunes Plus upgrade or re-purchase from a DRM-free store."},{question:"I bought the track after 2009 \u2014 why is it still DRM-protected?",answer:"All iTunes Store purchases after April 2009 should be DRM-free iTunes Plus. If a post-2009 purchase appears as .m4p, it may have been downloaded before the iTunes Plus upgrade was applied to your account. Try deleting the local copy and re-downloading from your Purchased list in the Music app \u2014 the re-download should be the DRM-free version."},{question:"Does Apple Music lossless streaming work differently from iTunes DRM?",answer:"Apple Music lossless downloads (ALAC) are separate from FairPlay DRM-protected purchases. Apple Music subscription downloads are protected by a subscription-based DRM that also cannot be played on CDJs. Only DRM-free purchased files (.m4a iTunes Plus) or files from other sources are CDJ-compatible. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305."}]};var u={path:"cdj-aiff-96khz-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: 96 kHz AIFF Not Playing on Pioneer CDJ",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on a 96 kHz AIFF file? Hi-res AIFF is not supported on any CDJ. Resample to 44.1 kHz or 48 kHz for CDJ playback.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: How to Fix 96 kHz AIFF Files for Pioneer CDJ Playback",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:'You receive a mastered AIFF at 96 kHz \u2014 straight from the label, lossless, perfectly formatted \u2014 and the CDJ immediately shows E-8305 "DATA FORMAT ERROR". The same issue applies here as with 96 kHz WAV: no Pioneer CDJ supports sample rates above 48 kHz for AIFF or WAV files, regardless of bit depth or model. AIFF at 96 kHz is common in mastering deliverables, label promo packs, and DJ pools that offer "high resolution" downloads.',technicalCause:"Pioneer CDJs support AIFF files at 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz only \u2014 identical to the WAV sample rate restriction. This applies to all bit depths (16-bit and 24-bit) and all current CDJ models: CDJ-3000, CDJ-2000NXS2, CDJ-2000NXS, XDJ-XZ, and XDJ-1000MK2. 96 kHz and 88.2 kHz AIFF files are common in mastering environments because AIFF is the native Apple/Mac audio format and Logic Pro defaults to AIFF for project audio. Label delivery specs often require 96 kHz masters. When a DJ receives a promo or distributes a personal rip from a 96 kHz Logic session as AIFF, the CDJ will reject it. rekordbox desktop supports 96 kHz AIFF preview and analysis \u2014 which is why the file appears fine in the library but fails on the physical unit.",manualSolution:{intro:"Resample the AIFF to 44.1 kHz. The AIFF container is preserved \u2014 only the sample rate changes.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI)",command:"ffmpeg -i input_96khz.aiff -acodec pcm_s24be -ar 44100 output_44khz.aiff",detail:"`-acodec pcm_s24be` sets 24-bit signed PCM big-endian \u2014 the correct codec for standard AIFF. AIFF uses big-endian byte order; using `pcm_s24be` (not `pcm_s24le`) ensures a proper AIFF container. `-ar 44100` resamples to 44.1 kHz. To output WAV instead, change the extension to `.wav` and use `-acodec pcm_s24le`."},{tool:"Logic Pro X (prevent on export)",detail:'If you are the producer exporting from Logic: in the Bounce dialog, set "Sample Rate" to 44.1 kHz and "Bit Depth" to 24 Bit. Logic defaults to the project sample rate (often 96 kHz for mastering sessions) \u2014 always explicitly set 44.1 kHz when bouncing for DJ use.'},{tool:"SoX (CLI)",command:"sox input_96khz.aiff -r 44100 output_44khz.aiff rate -v -s",detail:"SoX preserves the AIFF container format. `rate -v -s` uses the Very High Quality resampler. SoX is a reliable alternative to ffmpeg for AIFF-to-AIFF resampling."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready checks the sample rate of every AIFF file at upload \u2014 the same check applied to WAV files. AIFF files at 96 kHz or 88.2 kHz are automatically resampled to 44.1 kHz with a high-quality algorithm and re-packaged as standard AIFF PCM.",faq:[{question:"Is 96 kHz AIFF better quality than 44.1 kHz for club playback?",answer:"Not in any audible way on a dance-floor PA system. 96 kHz audio captures frequencies above 20 kHz which are beyond human hearing. A correctly performed sample rate conversion to 44.1 kHz preserves all audible frequency content. 24-bit AIFF at 44.1 kHz is the professional standard for DJ playback."},{question:"What is the difference between the 96 kHz AIFF guide and the 96 kHz WAV guide?",answer:"The underlying CDJ restriction is identical \u2014 44.1 / 48 kHz only for both formats. The technical difference is the ffmpeg codec flag: AIFF uses `pcm_s24be` (big-endian), WAV uses `pcm_s24le` (little-endian). See /cdj-wav-96khz-sample-rate-fix for the WAV version."},{question:"Does the CDJ-3000 support 96 kHz AIFF?",answer:"No. Despite CDJ-3000 FLAC support adding 96 kHz FLAC capability in firmware 1.20, WAV and AIFF remain limited to 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz on all models including the CDJ-3000. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305."},{question:"My label sends all promos as 96 kHz AIFF \u2014 what is the fastest workflow?",answer:'Run a batch ffmpeg command as part of your promo intake: `for f in *.aiff; do ffmpeg -i "$f" -acodec pcm_s24be -ar 44100 "44k_${f}"; done` This creates a 44.1 kHz copy of every AIFF in the folder with a "44k_" prefix, leaving the originals intact for archival.'}]};var p={path:"cdj-wav-low-sample-rate-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: Low Sample Rate WAV Fix (22 kHz, 11 kHz)",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on a WAV file with a sample rate below 32 kHz? Low sample rate audio from old games, samples, or voice recorders needs resampling.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: How to Fix Low Sample Rate WAV Files (22 kHz, 11 kHz) for Pioneer CDJ Playback",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:"Your CDJ throws E-8305 on a WAV file that plays fine everywhere else. The file might be a vocal sample, a sound effect, a retro game rip, or an old recording from a dictaphone or early digital recorder. If the sample rate is 22.05 kHz, 11.025 kHz, 8 kHz, or any other rate below 32 kHz, the CDJ will refuse to play it. Pioneer CDJs only support 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz \u2014 everything below that range triggers E-8305.",technicalCause:"Pioneer CDJ hardware decoders support WAV and AIFF files at exactly two sample rates: 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz. Sample rates below 32 kHz fall outside the supported range and trigger E-8305 during format validation. Low sample rate WAV files commonly originate from: old video game audio rips (22.05 kHz was standard for SNES, PlayStation 1, and early PC games), voice recorder exports (8 kHz, 11.025 kHz), early CD-ROM multimedia (22.05 kHz), sample pack content from the 1990s and early 2000s, and phone call recordings. Resampling from a low rate to 44.1 kHz does not recover frequency content that was never recorded (e.g. a 22 kHz file has no audio above 11 kHz by the Nyquist theorem), but it produces a CDJ-compatible file that plays the existing audio content correctly.",manualSolution:{intro:"Resample the file to 44.1 kHz. The audio content is unchanged \u2014 only the sample rate container is updated.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI)",command:"ffmpeg -i input_22khz.wav -acodec pcm_s24le -ar 44100 output_44khz.wav",detail:"`-ar 44100` resamples to 44.1 kHz. `-acodec pcm_s24le` outputs 24-bit PCM \u2014 upsampling from 16-bit to 24-bit adds no quality but ensures CDJ compatibility. For 16-bit output use `pcm_s16le`. Check the source sample rate first: `ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=sample_rate -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 input.wav`"},{tool:"SoX (CLI) \u2014 high quality resampling",command:"sox input_22khz.wav -r 44100 -b 24 output_44khz.wav rate -v -s",detail:"SoX's `rate -v -s` flags use the Very High Quality resampler with steep anti-aliasing. For upsampling from low rates this ensures no aliasing artefacts are introduced. `-b 24` sets 24-bit output."},{tool:"Audacity",detail:'Open the file in Audacity. At the bottom left of the window, click the sample rate dropdown (e.g. "22050 Hz") and change it to 44100 Hz. Audacity will resample in real time. Then export via File \u2192 Export \u2192 Export as WAV, selecting "Signed 24-bit PCM".'}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready reads the sample rate of every WAV and AIFF file at upload and flags files outside the 44.1 / 48 kHz supported range \u2014 both too high (96 kHz) and too low (below 32 kHz). Low sample rate files are automatically resampled to 44.1 kHz using a high-quality algorithm.",faq:[{question:"What sample rates do Pioneer CDJs support?",answer:"All current Pioneer CDJs (CDJ-3000, CDJ-2000NXS2, CDJ-2000NXS, XDJ-XZ, XDJ-1000MK2) support WAV and AIFF at 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz only. Both 96 kHz (too high) and 22 kHz or below (too low) trigger E-8305. 32 kHz is a borderline case \u2014 some CDJ models accept it, others do not."},{question:"Will resampling a 22 kHz file to 44.1 kHz improve the audio quality?",answer:"No. Resampling adds the missing frequency slots above 11 kHz but fills them with silence \u2014 no new frequency content is created. The audio will sound identical to the 22 kHz original, just in a CDJ-compatible container. If the source material sounds lo-fi, that character is preserved."},{question:"Why does my sample pack WAV play in Ableton but not on the CDJ?",answer:"Ableton Live and most DAWs support playback at any sample rate and automatically convert on the fly during playback. CDJ hardware decoders do not perform on-the-fly resampling \u2014 the file must match the supported sample rate before it is loaded."},{question:"Is there a quick way to check the sample rate of all files in a folder?",answer:'Run this in your terminal: `for f in *.wav; do echo "$f: $(ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=sample_rate -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 "$f")"; done` This prints the sample rate of every WAV file in the current directory. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305.'}]};var f={path:"cdj-mp3-sample-rate-fix",title:"CDJ E-8305: MP3 with Non-Standard Sample Rate Fix",description:"Pioneer CDJ shows E-8305 on an MP3 file? A non-standard sample rate outside MPEG-1/2 spec may be the cause. Learn how to re-encode to a CDJ-compatible rate.",h1:"CDJ Error E-8305: How to Fix MP3 Files with Non-Standard Sample Rates",errorDisplay:"E-8305",hook:"Your CDJ throws E-8305 on an MP3 file that plays fine in every software player. Most MP3 problems show up as E-8302 (corrupt frames) \u2014 but if the sample rate is outside the MPEG-1 or MPEG-2 specification, the CDJ decoder rejects the file with E-8305 before it even attempts to decode a single frame. This is a less common issue, but it reliably affects MP3 files produced by non-standard encoders or converted from unusual source sample rates.",technicalCause:"The MPEG-1 Audio Layer III specification defines three valid sample rates: 32 kHz, 44.1 kHz, and 48 kHz. MPEG-2 Audio (used for lower bitrates) extends this with 16 kHz, 22.05 kHz, and 24 kHz. Some non-standard encoders and audio processing tools produce MP3 files with sample rates outside these defined values \u2014 for example, 11.025 kHz, 8 kHz, or rates resulting from a poorly implemented sample rate conversion. Pioneer CDJs validate the sample rate field in the MP3 frame header against the MPEG specification during format checking. A non-compliant sample rate value causes the CDJ decoder to reject the file with E-8305. Desktop MP3 players are generally lenient and attempt playback regardless of the sample rate field. This issue is most common in MP3 files converted from low sample rate WAV sources (voice recordings, old game audio) by tools that do not perform proper resampling before encoding.",manualSolution:{intro:"Re-encode the MP3 with a standard MPEG-1 compliant sample rate. 44.1 kHz is the recommended target for music.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI)",command:"ffmpeg -i input_badrate.mp3 -acodec libmp3lame -ar 44100 -q:a 0 -id3v2_version 3 output_44k.mp3",detail:"`-ar 44100` resamples to 44.1 kHz before encoding. `-acodec libmp3lame` uses the LAME encoder, which writes ISO-compliant frames. `-q:a 0` sets maximum VBR quality. Note: re-encoding an MP3 to MP3 incurs generation loss. If the source WAV or AIFF is available, encode from that instead."},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 check sample rate first",command:"ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=sample_rate,codec_name -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 input.mp3",detail:"This confirms whether the sample rate is the cause. If it shows a non-standard value (e.g. 11025, 8000), re-encode at 44100. If the sample rate is 44100 or 48000 and E-8305 still appears, the cause may be a different format issue."},{tool:"Encode from WAV source (best quality)",command:"ffmpeg -i source.wav -acodec libmp3lame -ar 44100 -b:a 320k -id3v2_version 3 output.mp3",detail:"If the original WAV source is available, always encode from that. `-ar 44100` in combination with a WAV input ensures the output is MPEG-1 compliant at 44.1 kHz. `-b:a 320k` sets 320 kbps CBR."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready validates the sample rate field of every MP3 frame header against the MPEG-1/2 specification. Files with non-standard sample rates are automatically re-encoded to 44.1 kHz using LAME at the original bitrate.",faq:[{question:"What sample rates are valid for MP3 files on Pioneer CDJs?",answer:"For MPEG-1 MP3: 32 kHz, 44.1 kHz, 48 kHz. For MPEG-2 MP3 (lower bitrate): 16 kHz, 22.05 kHz, 24 kHz. 44.1 kHz is the most widely supported and recommended for music. Any value outside these defined rates will trigger E-8305 on Pioneer CDJ hardware."},{question:"How does a non-standard sample rate get into an MP3?",answer:"Usually by converting from a non-standard WAV source without proper resampling. For example, converting an 8 kHz voice recording WAV to MP3 using a basic tool that writes the source sample rate directly into the MP3 header instead of resampling to a valid MPEG rate. This is a bug in the encoding tool, not in the source audio."},{question:"Is this the same as the E-8305 on WAV files with 96 kHz?",answer:"Related but distinct. Both are sample rate incompatibilities triggering E-8305. The WAV 96 kHz issue is about hi-res audio above the CDJ limit. The MP3 sample rate issue is about values that are outside the MPEG specification entirely \u2014 often too low (8 kHz, 11 kHz) rather than too high. See all E-8305 causes at /cdj-error-e-8305."}]};var m={path:"cdj-aiff-chunk-order-fix",title:"CDJ AIFF Loading Problem: Non-Standard Chunk Order Fix",description:"AIFF file loads slowly or causes sporadic E-8302 on Pioneer CDJs? A non-standard chunk order in the AIFF container can cause loading issues. Here's the fix.",h1:"CDJ AIFF Loading Issues: How to Fix Non-Standard AIFF Chunk Order",errorDisplay:"",hook:"Your AIFF file loads unusually slowly on the CDJ, or occasionally triggers a sporadic E-8302 that disappears when you try again. There is no consistent error \u2014 sometimes it loads, sometimes it does not. One underdiagnosed cause is a non-standard chunk order inside the AIFF container. Most software writes and reads AIFF chunks in any order, but some CDJ firmware versions expect the COMM chunk to appear before the SSND (audio data) chunk and behave unpredictably when it does not.",technicalCause:"An AIFF file is a container of named chunks. The two essential chunks are COMM (format descriptor: sample rate, bit depth, channels) and SSND (the audio sample data). The AIFF specification does not mandate a strict chunk order, but it recommends placing COMM before SSND. Some audio tools \u2014 particularly older versions of Peak, Bias, and certain hardware recorders \u2014 write SSND before COMM or insert other chunks between them. Pioneer CDJ firmware parsers across all models are known to handle non-standard chunk order poorly: loading times increase as the firmware seeks for the COMM chunk, and in some cases the decoder fails with E-8302. NXS-generation players (CDJ-2000NXS, CDJ-2000NXS2, CDJ-900NXS, CDJ-900NXS2, CDJ-Tour1) are most susceptible. The CDJ-3000 is more tolerant but can still show slow loading with large AIFF files where SSND precedes COMM. This is a less common issue than the sample rate or codec problems, but it disproportionately affects AIFF files produced by older Mac recording software and hardware samplers.",manualSolution:{intro:"The fix is to rewrite the AIFF file with the standard chunk order (COMM before SSND). This is a lossless container rewrite \u2014 no audio data changes.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg (CLI) \u2014 rewrite chunk order",command:"ffmpeg -i input_badorder.aiff -acodec copy output_fixed.aiff",detail:"`-acodec copy` copies the audio stream without re-encoding. ffmpeg rewrites the AIFF container with standard chunk order (COMM before SSND) when it remuxes the file. This is a fast, lossless operation \u2014 only the container structure is modified."},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 verify chunk order first",command:'ffprobe -v trace input.aiff 2>&1 | grep -E "tag|offset"',detail:"This command shows the chunk tags and their byte offsets in the file. If SSND appears at a lower offset than COMM, the chunk order is non-standard. For most users it is simpler to run the rewrite unconditionally."},{tool:"SoX (CLI)",command:"sox input_badorder.aiff output_fixed.aiff",detail:"SoX always writes AIFF files with COMM before SSND. If the source is already uncompressed AIFF PCM, SoX performs a lossless copy with correct chunk order. Specify bit depth explicitly to avoid any format change: `sox input.aiff -b 24 output.aiff`."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready checks the AIFF chunk order of every uploaded AIFF file and automatically rewrites non-standard files using a lossless container rewrite. This prevents the sporadic loading issues and slow seek behaviour across all Pioneer CDJ models.",faq:[{question:"How common is non-standard AIFF chunk order?",answer:"Relatively rare in modern files \u2014 most current software (Logic Pro, Ableton, ffmpeg, SoX) writes standard chunk order. It is more common in AIFF files from the late 1990s and early 2000s created with Bias Peak, MOTU AudioDesk, or exported from hardware samplers (Akai S1000/S3000, E-mu E4). If you are working with vintage sample libraries or old studio archives, this check is worth running."},{question:"Is the AIFF chunk order rewrite truly lossless?",answer:"Yes. The audio sample data in the SSND chunk is not modified \u2014 only the order of chunks in the container file is changed. The output file is bit-for-bit identical in audio content to the input."},{question:"Can non-standard chunk order cause E-8302?",answer:"Sporadically, yes. On Pioneer CDJ firmware, a non-standard chunk order can cause the decoder initialisation to fail, producing E-8302 \u2014 NXS-generation models are most susceptible. Because the failure is not consistent (it depends on how the firmware parser handles the seek), the same file may load on one attempt and fail on another. If you see intermittent E-8302 on AIFF files that otherwise seem valid, chunk order is a likely cause."},{question:"Does this issue affect WAV files?",answer:"Rarely. WAV (RIFF) files have a similar chunk structure, and the fmt chunk should precede the data chunk. Most WAV writers follow this convention. The non-standard chunk order issue is primarily documented for AIFF on Pioneer CDJs. For WAV loading problems, see /cdj-wav-corrupt-header or /cdj-wav-extensible-fix."}]};var y={path:"cdj-mp3-low-bitrate-quality",title:"CDJ MP3 Low Bitrate: Quality Warning for Club Playback",description:"No error code, but your MP3 sounds bad on a club PA? Low bitrate MP3 below 128 kbps is audibly degraded on large sound systems. Here's what to check.",h1:"CDJ MP3 Low Bitrate: Why Sub-128 kbps MP3s Sound Bad on Club Sound Systems",errorDisplay:"",hook:"Your track plays without any error on the CDJ, but on the club's PA it sounds dull, artefacty, or lacks the high-frequency energy you hear at home. There is no E-8304 or E-8305 \u2014 the CDJ accepts the file without complaint. The issue is MP3 bitrate. Files encoded below 128 kbps have audible compression artefacts that become clearly noticeable on a loud, high-quality sound system even if they sound acceptable on headphones or small speakers.",technicalCause:'MP3 compression works by discarding audio information the encoder determines is perceptually less important. At high bitrates (320 kbps CBR or VBR V0) this process is nearly transparent. At bitrates below 128 kbps, the encoder must discard significantly more data \u2014 resulting in: loss of high-frequency content above 10\u201315 kHz (audible as a dull, muffled top end), pre-echo artefacts on transient sounds (clicks, snares, hi-hats), and "metallic" or "watery" distortion on sustained sounds. On a club PA system \u2014 particularly on high-powered subs and tweeters \u2014 these artefacts are amplified and become clearly audible. Pioneer CDJs accept and play MP3 files at any bitrate the MPEG specification allows (8 kbps minimum). Low bitrate is therefore a quality warning, not a compatibility error. Boothready flags files below 128 kbps as a WARNING (not ERROR) to give DJs advance notice before a gig.',manualSolution:{intro:"There is no way to recover quality lost during lossy encoding. The only solutions are to source a higher quality version of the file or re-encode from a lossless source if available.",steps:[{tool:"Check the bitrate first",command:"ffprobe -v error -select_streams a:0 -show_entries stream=bit_rate,codec_name -of default=noprint_wrappers=1 input.mp3",detail:"This prints the bitrate in bits per second. Divide by 1000 for kbps. A result of 128000 or above is generally acceptable for club playback. Below 128000 \u2014 particularly below 96000 \u2014 is noticeably degraded on large systems."},{tool:"Source a higher quality version",detail:"The most effective fix is to source a higher quality version. Check your original purchase or download source for a WAV, AIFF, or 320 kbps MP3 option. Beatport, Bandcamp, and Traxsource offer WAV downloads for most releases. Streaming rips and YouTube-to-MP3 conversions are a common source of low bitrate files."},{tool:"Re-encode from lossless source (if available)",command:"ffmpeg -i source.wav -acodec libmp3lame -q:a 0 -id3v2_version 3 output_vbr_max.mp3",detail:"If you have the original WAV or AIFF master, re-encoding at `-q:a 0` (LAME VBR maximum quality, ~245 kbps average) produces a transparent result. Do NOT re-encode a low bitrate MP3 to a higher bitrate MP3 \u2014 this does not recover quality and only inflates the file size. Generation loss from lossy-to-lossy encoding makes the artefacts worse, not better."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready flags MP3 files below 128 kbps as a WARNING in the analysis report. No auto-fix is applied \u2014 re-encoding a low bitrate MP3 to a higher bitrate would not recover quality and could make artefacts worse. The warning gives you actionable information: find a better source for these tracks before the gig.",faq:[{question:"What is the minimum recommended MP3 bitrate for club use?",answer:"320 kbps CBR or LAME VBR V0 (~245 kbps average) is the recommended standard for professional DJ use. 256 kbps is acceptable and generally transparent. 192 kbps is audible to trained ears on a high-quality system. 128 kbps is the practical minimum \u2014 below this the artefacts are clearly audible on a club PA."},{question:"Can I make a low bitrate MP3 sound better by converting to WAV?",answer:"No. Converting a 128 kbps MP3 to WAV produces a large file with identical audio quality to the source MP3. The conversion to WAV does not restore any of the frequency content or dynamics lost during the original MP3 encoding. The only way to get better quality is to source a higher quality version of the recording."},{question:"Does a low bitrate MP3 cause any CDJ error code?",answer:"No. Pioneer CDJs play MP3 files at any valid MPEG bitrate without throwing an error. Low bitrate is purely an audio quality issue, not a compatibility issue. Boothready flags it as a warning rather than an error for this reason."},{question:"How do I avoid low bitrate files in my library going forward?",answer:"Always buy from Beatport, Bandcamp, or Traxsource and select WAV or AIFF where available. If buying MP3, check that the listing specifies 320 kbps. Avoid streaming rips, YouTube conversions, and file sharing sources \u2014 these are the most common sources of sub-128 kbps files in DJ libraries."}]};var g={path:"cdj-id3-encoding-fix",title:"CDJ Garbled Track Info: ID3 Tag Encoding Fix (UTF-8)",description:"Artist name, track title, or album shows question marks or garbage characters on your Pioneer CDJ display? ID3 tag encoding is the cause. Here's how to fix it.",h1:"CDJ Garbled Track Info: How to Fix ID3 Tag Encoding Issues on Pioneer CDJs",errorDisplay:"",hook:`Your track title shows as "?????" or a string of strange symbols on the CDJ display. The audio plays fine \u2014 no error code \u2014 but the artist name, track title, or album field is unreadable. This is an ID3 tag encoding problem. The text stored in the MP3's metadata tags uses a character encoding that the CDJ display cannot render correctly, typically because the tags were written in a legacy encoding like Latin-1 (ISO-8859-1) or a Windows codepage instead of UTF-8 or UTF-16.`,technicalCause:"ID3 tags (the metadata stored inside MP3 files) include a text encoding byte that declares how the tag values are encoded. The ID3v2 specification supports four encodings: ISO-8859-1 (Latin-1), UTF-16 with BOM, UTF-16BE, and UTF-8. Pioneer CDJs display tags correctly for UTF-8 and UTF-16 (ID3v2.3 and ID3v2.4). Problems arise in three scenarios: (1) Tags written in a non-Western Windows codepage (e.g. CP932 for Japanese, CP1251 for Cyrillic) but declared as ISO-8859-1 \u2014 the CDJ reads the encoding byte, assumes Latin-1, and cannot interpret the characters. (2) Very old tags using ID3v1 (128-byte fixed-length tags at the end of the file) with no encoding declaration \u2014 CDJs display these as raw bytes. (3) Tags written by rekordbox or Traktor on one system and re-written by another tool that changes the encoding without updating the encoding byte. No error code is produced \u2014 the CDJ simply renders the raw bytes as whatever character the font table maps them to, producing garbled output.",manualSolution:{intro:"The fix is to re-write the ID3 tags in UTF-8 encoding. This does not affect the audio data.",steps:[{tool:"mid3iconv (Python, CLI) \u2014 Japanese/CJK tags",command:"mid3iconv -e CP932 -d input.mp3",detail:'mid3iconv is part of the mutagen library and converts ID3 tags from a specified source encoding to UTF-8. `-e CP932` specifies the source encoding (CP932 for Japanese Shift-JIS, CP1251 for Cyrillic, CP1252 for Western European Windows). `-d` performs a dry run first \u2014 remove it to write the changes. Install via `pip install mutagen`. For a batch convert: `find . -name "*.mp3" -exec mid3iconv -e CP932 {} \\;`'},{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 rewrite tags as ID3v2.3 UTF-8",command:"ffmpeg -i input.mp3 -acodec copy -id3v2_version 3 -write_id3v1 0 output_fixed.mp3",detail:"`-id3v2_version 3` writes ID3v2.3 tags, which are most compatible across CDJ models. `-write_id3v1 0` removes any ID3v1 tag that might override the v2 tag on older CDJ firmware. `-acodec copy` copies audio without re-encoding. Note: ffmpeg copies the existing tag text as-is \u2014 if the source encoding is already wrong (misidentified codepage), you may need mid3iconv first to fix the character data before ffmpeg rewrites the container."},{tool:"Mp3tag (GUI, Windows/macOS)",detail:"Mp3tag is a free GUI tag editor with built-in encoding conversion. Select all tracks \u2192 Tools \u2192 Convert Encoding \u2192 choose source encoding and set target to UTF-8. Mp3tag writes ID3v2.3 tags by default (configurable under Tools \u2192 Options \u2192 Tags \u2192 MPEG). Download at mp3tag.de."},{tool:"rekordbox \u2014 re-analyse tracks",detail:"After fixing the tag encoding with one of the tools above, re-import or re-analyse the tracks in rekordbox. rekordbox stores tag data in its own database \u2014 it must re-read the fixed tags from the file before the CDJ display will update."}]},boothreadySolution:"Boothready scans ID3 tags for encoding declarations and validates that text fields are correctly encoded as UTF-8 or UTF-16. Tracks with encoding mismatches are flagged with the likely source encoding and auto-fixed by re-writing the tags in UTF-8.",faq:[{question:"Does ID3 tag encoding affect CDJ audio playback?",answer:"No. Garbled track info is a display problem only \u2014 the audio plays correctly regardless of tag encoding. There is no error code and no playback failure. The only impact is on the artist/title/album display on the CDJ screen and in the rekordbox library."},{question:"Which CDJ models are affected by ID3 encoding issues?",answer:"All CDJ models display tags \u2014 so all are affected. CDJ-3000 and CDJ-2000NXS2 handle UTF-8 and UTF-16 ID3v2.3/v2.4 tags correctly. ID3v1 tags and incorrectly declared codepages cause garbled display on all models. CDJ-3000 is slightly more tolerant of encoding inconsistencies than CDJ-2000NXS2 in some firmware versions."},{question:"Why do my Japanese track titles show correctly in rekordbox but not on the CDJ?",answer:"rekordbox on macOS uses Core Text, which attempts multiple encoding fallbacks and often renders Japanese characters correctly even when the encoding declaration is wrong. CDJ firmware renders tags strictly according to the encoding byte in the ID3 header. The fix is to ensure the encoding byte correctly declares UTF-8 or UTF-16, which CDJs handle natively."},{question:"What is the difference between ID3v1 and ID3v2?",answer:"ID3v1 is a legacy 128-byte block appended to the end of the MP3 with fixed-length fields and no encoding declaration. ID3v2 (v2.3 and v2.4) is a more flexible tag at the start of the file that supports Unicode, longer fields, album art, and explicit encoding declarations. Pioneer CDJs read ID3v2 tags preferentially. If both v1 and v2 are present, v2 takes precedence on CDJ-2000NXS2 and CDJ-3000. Always use ID3v2.3 for maximum CDJ compatibility."}]};var b={path:"cdj-wav-24bit-cdj900-compatibility",title:"CDJ-900 / CDJ-900NXS: 24-bit WAV Compatibility Warning",description:"Are you targeting CDJ-900 or CDJ-900NXS players? 24-bit WAV support is limited on these models. Learn which format is safe for older Pioneer CDJ hardware.",h1:"CDJ-900 and CDJ-900NXS: 24-bit WAV Compatibility \u2014 What You Need to Know",errorDisplay:"",hook:"Your 24-bit WAV plays perfectly on CDJ-2000NXS2 and CDJ-3000 \u2014 but on CDJ-900 or CDJ-900NXS players at a venue, it either refuses to load or plays back at the wrong pitch or speed. This is not a corrupt file or a format error. It is a model-specific limitation: the CDJ-900 and CDJ-900NXS have incomplete 24-bit WAV support that can produce unexpected behaviour depending on sample rate and firmware version.",technicalCause:"Pioneer introduced the CDJ-900 in 2010 as a mid-range player. Its hardware decoder has limited support for 24-bit WAV compared to the CDJ-2000 series. Documented limitations on CDJ-900 and CDJ-900NXS include: 24-bit WAV files at 48 kHz may play at incorrect pitch on certain firmware versions, 24-bit WAV files above a certain file size (long tracks) may fail to load, and 24-bit WAV with WAVE_FORMAT_EXTENSIBLE headers (common in DAW exports) will trigger E-8305 on CDJ-900 just as on all other CDJ models. The CDJ-900NXS (2013) improved 24-bit support but did not fully resolve all edge cases. No error code is thrown for the pitch/speed issue \u2014 the file loads and plays, but at the wrong rate. This issue does not affect CDJ-2000, CDJ-2000NXS, CDJ-2000NXS2, or CDJ-3000, all of which fully support 24-bit WAV at 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz.",manualSolution:{intro:"If you regularly play on CDJ-900 or CDJ-900NXS, convert your library to 16-bit WAV to guarantee compatibility across all Pioneer CDJ models.",steps:[{tool:"ffmpeg \u2014 convert to 16-bit WAV (universal compatibility)",command:"ffmpeg -i input_24bit.wav -acodec pcm_s16le -ar 44100 -dither_method triangular output_16bit.wav",detail:'`-acodec pcm_s16le` sets 16-bit signed PCM little-endian \u2014 supported on all CDJ models without exception. `-dither_method triangular` applies triangular dither during the bit depth reduction, which minimises quantisation noise. `-ar 44100` ensures 44.1 kHz output. For a batch convert: `for f in *.wav; do ffmpeg -i "$f" -acodec pcm_s16le -ar 44100 -dither_method triangular "16bit_${f}"; done`'},{tool:"Check which CDJ models are at the venue",detail:"Before converting your library, confirm which CDJ models are installed at the venues you play. CDJ-900 and CDJ-900NXS are increasingly rare in professional clubs (most venues upgraded to CDJ-2000NXS or NXS2 by 2018). If you only play on CDJ-2000NXS2 or CDJ-3000, 24-bit WAV is fully supported and no conversion is needed."}]},boothreadySolution:"In Boothready, you can set your target CDJ model when creating a job. If CDJ-900 or CDJ-900NXS is included in the target model set, Boothready flags 24-bit WAV files as a WARNING and optionally converts them to 16-bit for maximum compatibility. If only CDJ-2000NXS2 or CDJ-3000 is targeted, 24-bit WAV is passed through without any warning.",faq:[{question:"Is 24-bit WAV safe to use on all Pioneer CDJs?",answer:"On CDJ-2000, CDJ-2000NXS, CDJ-2000NXS2, and CDJ-3000: yes, 24-bit WAV at 44.1 kHz and 48 kHz is fully supported. On CDJ-900 and CDJ-900NXS: limited support \u2014 24-bit at 44.1 kHz generally works, but 24-bit at 48 kHz may cause pitch issues on some firmware versions. 16-bit WAV at 44.1 kHz is universally safe across all CDJ models."},{question:"Will converting 24-bit to 16-bit noticeably reduce audio quality?",answer:"With proper dithering, the reduction from 24-bit to 16-bit is inaudible on a club PA system. 16-bit PCM provides 96 dB of dynamic range, which exceeds the dynamic range of any club playback environment. Apply triangular dither (`-dither_method triangular` in ffmpeg) to minimise quantisation noise during the conversion."},{question:"Which CDJ-900 firmware version fixed the 24-bit issue?",answer:"Pioneer released firmware updates for CDJ-900 that improved 24-bit WAV handling, but documentation on exactly which firmware version resolves which specific 24-bit issue is not publicly detailed. The safest approach for CDJ-900 venues is to use 16-bit WAV rather than relying on firmware version detection."},{question:"Does this issue affect AIFF files on CDJ-900?",answer:"24-bit AIFF on CDJ-900 has similar limitations to 24-bit WAV. The safest format for CDJ-900 venues is 16-bit WAV or 16-bit AIFF at 44.1 kHz. For all other CDJ models, 24-bit WAV or AIFF is fully supported."}]};var w=[t,o,a,i,r,s,n,l,d,c,h,u,p,f,m,y,g,b],oe=Object.fromEntries(w.map(e=>[e.path,e]));export{oe as a};
